The change of keyframes in an odometry-like measurement model is simply the removal of an augmented state xi followed by the addition of another augmented state with the same Bi. Since we allow multiple relative measurements that correspond to the same augmented state, contrast to [11], augmented states are not deleted after measurement updates (Sect. IV-D).
This state augmentation formulation works well in an EKF setting, however, it poses issues when we try to apply it to the UKF. Since the addition of a new augmented state (8) is essentially a copy of the main state. The resulting covariance matrix PË‡ + will not be positive deï¬nite, and the Cholesky decomposition (5) for state propagation will fail (non-unique). We now wish to have something that is similar to the Jacobian matrices for EKF, but without explicitly computing the Jacobians.

A. State Augmentation for Multiple Relative Measurements
Since a relative measurement depends both the current and past states, it is a violation of the fundamental assumption in the Kalman ï¬lter that the measurement should only depend on the current state. One way to deal with this is through state augmentation [11], where a copy of the past state is maintained in the ï¬lter. Here we present an extension of [11] to handle arbitrary number of relative measurement models with the possiblity that multiple measurements correspond to the same augmented state. Our generic ï¬ltering framework allows convenient setup, and facilitates addition and removal of absolute and relative measurement models.
Note that a measurement may not affect all components in the state x. For example, a visual odometry only affects the 6-DOF pose, not the velocity or the bias terms. We deï¬ne the ith augmented state as xi âˆˆ Rni , ni â‰¤ n. xi is an arbitrary subset of x. We deï¬ne a binary selection matrix Bi of size ni Ã—n, such that xi = Bix. Consider a time instant, there are I augmented states in the ï¬lter, along with the covariance:

